ess with authorization2star  aThe National Health Service has provided Britain’s healthcare since 1948. This institution has been the subject of tense political debate since its inception and has undergone a number of complex reforms and restructures. But the meanings of the NHS are not only – or even primarily – lived out in politics. Nearly every Briton comes into contact with the NHS – from cradle to grave – and this system of healthcare shapes society, culture and everyday life. This book charts these multiple meanings, looking at the NHS as a site of work, activism and consumerism, as a space and in cultural representations. Looking in these ways, the book shows how and why the NHS has become a symbol of Britishness and an object of fierce protectiveness, even love, today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPublic healthxSocial aspectszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aPublic healthzGreat BritainxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAneurin Bevan.  aNHS activism.  aNHS history.  aNHS staff.  aNational Health Service.  acultural history.  amodern British history.  apost-war welfare state.  aprescriptions.  awaiting rooms.1 aBivins, Roberta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrane, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrane, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDodworth, Kathy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErcia, Angelo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHand, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHand, Jane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLogan, Katey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb